<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ECONOMIC REFORMS AT RISK AS CHINESE MARKETS FALL</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Chinese markets continued their slump on Wednesday, with the main Shanghai index falling more than 8 percent in early trading, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/business/international/stock-sell-off-unabated-in-china.html"> David Barboza writes in The New York Times</a>. It <b> closed 5.9 percent lower</b>. Nearly <b> half the listings on Chinaâs exchanges stopped trading</b> by Wednesday morning, most of them at the request of companies, although some listings were also suspended by regulators. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now that the countryâs stock markets are sinking sharply, the government of President Xi Jinping is facing âa searing test of its commitment to overhaul the countryâs financial system and open up the state-controlled economy,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/08/business/markets-dive-could-delay-economic-reforms-in-china.html"> Keith Bradsher and Chris Buckley write in The New York Times</a>. âFor a government that loves absolute control, getting pushed around by the markets is an <b> unsettling experience</b>,â they write, and the government may want to try to maintain control if the stock market weakness continues. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Beijing has moved quickly to try to prop up share prices, with the latest measures coming on Wednesday morning, when the China Securities Finance Corporation said it would provide <b> more financing for purchases of shares in small and medium-size companies</b>, while continuing to support shares of large companies. Soon afterward, the Chinese central bank said it would continue <b> providing liquidity for the finance corporation</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Tao Ran, a professor of economics at Renmin University in Beijing, said the stock market rout would probably dampen the Chinese governmentâs appetite for deeper changes to the economy, but added that the downturn actually <b> strengthened the case for such changes</b>, Mr. Bradsher and Mr. Buckley write. âPeople may say that this strengthens the case for not changing things,â Professor Tao said. âBut I think that this has happened exactly because <b> reform has not been done in the right way</b>.â He added: âSo far the rescue policy has not been working well. They <b> overestimated their own capacity to control</b>, and now people are voting with their feet.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>SUNDAY DEADLINE FOR GREECE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> European leaders have set what they called a final deadline for Greece, <a href=" //www.nytimes.com/2015/07/08/business/international/greece-debt-eurozone-meeting.html"> Andrew Higgins and James Kanter write in The New York Times</a>. If the country <b> cannot reach an agreement on a bailout by Sunday</b>, said Donald Tusk, the president of the European Council, it risks âthe <b> bankruptcy of Greece</b> and the insolvency of its banking system.â Mr. Tusk said that the government of Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras had until Thursday to <b> deliver a new plan to Greeceâs creditors</b>. âUntil now I have avoided talking about deadlines,â Mr. Tusk, a former prime minister of Poland, told reporters. âBut tonight I have to say it loud and clear â <b> the final deadline ends this week</b>.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nicolas VÃ©ron, a senior fellow at Bruegel, a research organization in Brussels, said time was running out to keep Greece in the currency union, Mr. Higgins and Mr. Kanter write. The continuation of emergency financing for Greek banks by the European Central Bank âis <b> clearly dependent on the likelihood of an agreement</b> between Greece and its creditors,â Mr. VÃ©ron said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Jean-Claude Juncker, the president of the European Commission, the European Unionâs executive arm, said late Tuesday night that his staff had drawn up plans for several possible outcomes, including Greeceâs exit from the eurozone. Mr. Juncker also <b> expressed his fury</b> at officials of Syriza, the left-wing party led by Mr. Tsipras, for their attacks on Greeceâs creditors, particularly one by the recently departed finance minister, Yanis Varoufakis, accusing creditors of âterrorism.â âWho are they and who do they think I am?â Mr. Juncker said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That same fury was evident in the European Parliament on Wednesday after Mr. Tsipras told parliament members that he was not blaming âwicked foreigners,â <a href="//www.ft.com/intl/fastft/356801"> The Financial Times reports</a>. In response, Manfred Weber, a political ally of Chancellor Angela Merkel of Germany, criticized Mr. Tsipras for not condemning the âterroristâ comment, <a href="//on.ft.com/1fmHzll"> the newspaper reports</a>. Then he added: âYou are <b> destroying confidence in Europe</b>. Youâre talking about dignity, but dignity means truth, honesty. You said that the banks are closing because the evil E.C.B. is ratcheting up pressure. You said the banks would be open on Tuesday, it is now Wednesday. You are not being honest with the Greek people.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BARCLAYS C.E.O. IS STEPPING DOWN</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Barclays said on Wednesday that its chief executive, Antony Jenkins, was stepping down as the British bank sought to shake up its leadership, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/business/dealbook/antony-jenkins-to-step-down-as-barclays-chief-executive.html"> Chad Bray writes in DealBook</a>. Barclays is the <b> latest European bank to make changes at the top</b>, with Credit Suisse, Standard Chartered and Deutsche Bank all replacing their chief executives this year as banks look to adjust to tighter regulatory scrutiny and to move beyond a series of legacy issues and investigations that have eaten into earnings. Mr. Jenkins, who replaced Robert E. Diamond Jr. as chief executive during an interest rate-rigging scandal in 2012, will step down on July 17. A search for a successor to Mr. Jenkins is underway, Barclays said, and in the interim, John McFarlane, who replaced David Walker as the Barclays chairman this year, will become executive chairman. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Federal Reserve will release the minutes from the <b> June policy-making meeting</b> at 2 p.m. <b> Alcoa</b> is among the companies reporting earnings today. <b> John Williams</b>, the president of the Federal Reserve of San Francisco and voting member of the Fedâs policy-setting committee, will speak about the economic outlook before the International Conference of Commercial Bank Economists in Los Angeles at 11 a.m. (2 p.m. E.D.T.). <b> Jacob J. Lew</b>, the Treasury secretary, discusses financial stability and the economy five years after the Dodd-Frank Act at the Brookings Institution at 8:45 a.m. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b> On the Hill:</b> The Senate Banking Committee will hold a hearing titled âThe Role of the Financial Stability Board in the United States Regulatory Frameworkâ at 10 a.m. A House Financial Services subcommittee will hold a hearing titled âExamining the Designation and Regulation of Bank Holding Company Systemically Important Financial Institutionsâ at 1 p.m.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>UNEXPECTED CONSEQUENCES OF LEVERAGED LOAN CRACKDOWN </strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> In cracking down on leveraged loans, the kind of debt associated most commonly with buyouts by private equity firms, federal regulators are finding out just how difficult it is âto stamp out what are deemed risky practices and how regulation can lead to unexpected consequences,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/08/business/dealbook/balancing-act-for-regulators-seeking-to-curb-leveraged-loans.html"> Steven Davidoff Solomon writes in the Deal Professor column</a>. Regulators have seen some success in getting banks to pull back from lending to private equity firms after cracking down on loans that exceeded the limit of six times a companyâs earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization, or Ebitda. Now, however, <b> unregulated financial institutions</b>, or the so-called shadow banking system, have stepped into the breach, Professor Solomon writes. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of the unexpected beneficiaries of the crackdown on leveraged lending is <b> Jefferies</b>, which, as an investment bank, is <b> not subject to the loan regulations</b>. For example, in the purchase of TransFirst by Vista Equity Partners last year, Jefferies was able to finance a loan that was <b> 7.4 times Ebitda</b>. Other winners have been <b> business development companies</b>, which are also not bound by the leverage loan rules.<br />
</p>
</div>
